\begin_layout Standard
More recently, 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citet{bib:arcsk2017}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 have introduced the probem of identifying a single arm from among the best 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-armed bandit. This formulation is particularly useful when the number of arms is large, and in fact is a viable alternative even when the number of arms is 
\shape italic
infinite
\shape default
. In many practical scenarios, however, it is required to identify more than a single good arm. For example, imagine that a company needs to complete a task that is too large to be accomplished by a single worker, but which can be broken into 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 subtasks, each capable of being completed by one worker. Suppose there are a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

 workers, and an indepdendent pilot survey has revealed that at least 
\begin_inset Formula $15\%$
\end_inset

 of them have the skills to complete the subtask. To address the company's need, surely it would 
\shape italic
suffice
\shape default
 to identify the best 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 workers for the subtask. However, if workers are to be identified based on a skill test that has stochastic outcomes, it would be unnecessarily expensive to indeed identify the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

best subset
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

. Rather, it would be enough to merely identify any 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 workers from among the best 
\begin_inset Formula $150$
\end_inset

. This is precisely the problem we consider in our paper: identifying any 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 out of the best 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 arms in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-armed bandit. In addition to distributed crowdsourcing
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{Tran-Thanh+SRJ:2014}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, applications of this problem include the management of large sensor networks
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{Mousavi+HHD:2016}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, wherein multiple reliable sensors must be identified using minimal testing, and in drug design
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep[Chapter 43]{McDuffie+OJ:2016}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, to identify a promising set of candidate biomarkers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem assumes equal significance from a theoretical standpoint, since it generalises both the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

best subset selection
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{bib:explorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (taking 
\begin_inset Formula $k = m$
\end_inset

) and that of selecting a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

single arm from the best subset
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{bib:arcsk2017}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (taking 
\begin_inset Formula $k = 1$
\end_inset

). Unlike best subset selection, the problem remains feasible to solve even when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large or infinite, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $m/n$
\end_inset

 is some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho > 0$
\end_inset

. Traditionally, infinite-armed bandits have been tackled by resorting to side information such as distances between arms
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{bib:agracntregret,bib:kleincntregret}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or the structure of their distribution of rewards
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{bib:wang2008}
\end_layout

\end_inset

. This approach introduces additional parameters, which might not be easy to tune in practice. Alternatively, good arms can be reached merely by selecting arms 
\shape italic
at random
\shape default
 and testing them by pulling. This latter approach has been applied successfully both in the regret-minimisation setting
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{Herschkorn+PR:1996}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and in the fixed-confidence setting
\begin_inset space ~

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
citep{bib:sergiu,bib:arcsk2017}
\end_layout

\end_inset

. Our formulation paves the way for identifying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

many
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (in the top 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 among 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) arms in this manner.
